So, let’s not waste a minute and get right into it.

00:01:04.067 --> 00:01:07.497
The Mediterranean Sea is full of wonderful islands.

00:01:08.107 --> 00:01:12.506
Some of them are tiny, barely more than rocky outcrops,

00:01:12.706 --> 00:01:16.366
while others have been important trading hubs for centuries.

00:01:17.126 --> 00:01:20.816
Almost all of them belong to another country.

00:01:21.706 --> 00:01:27.868
Greece claims almost half of them, Croatia another 15 to 20%.

00:01:28.626 --> 00:01:33.346
The rest are divided between Italy, France, and a

00:01:33.346 --> 00:01:35.966
bunch of other countries surrounding the Mediterranean.

00:01:36.546 --> 00:01:43.556
But there are two exceptions—two islands that are fully independent, sovereign states.

00:01:44.596 --> 00:01:49.756
One is Malta, the small island just south of Sicily that has been

00:01:49.756 --> 00:01:54.266
part of various different empires but is now an independent country.

00:01:55.256 --> 00:02:01.826
Now, one thing not everyone knows about Malta is that it isn’t just one island; there

00:02:01.826 --> 00:02:07.646
are actually five islands: the main one, called Malta, a smaller and sleepier one,

00:02:07.976 --> 00:02:15.096
called Gozo, and three more uninhabited ones, or to get even more technical, one of

